			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I do suspect though, that a random spawning would tend to preserve a spawn's integrity. Said more directly, it would tend to require us to continually break a spawn OR at the very least deal with unexpected add's. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
That's basically the sum of it.  At this point, in a (non-LDoN) dungeon crawl and some outdoor zones, you basically clear a location and pull to it, until the place you're sitting respawns predicably and you start all over.  Randomized timers would destroy that safety.  The room could repop, partially or fully, at *any* time (assuming the minimum side of the timer was pretty low).  That single pull of yours could turn into a gigantor train with respawns along your "cleared" pulling path.  It would essentially force crawling for any margin of safety, trying to move out from an area before the low end of the timer caught up with you.  Or just xping in safe/trivial places where numerous adds are tolerable.
<br />

<br />
If used in a highly limited environment, it could be nice for a little flavor, flare, and challenge.  If it became mainstream, either retroactively or in most new content, it would be a royal pain.  A large aspect of success would go from being dependant on planning ahead with spawn break pattern to dependant on luck in respawn timers.  A change decreasing skill factor and increasing luck factor is generally not a good change, imo.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
